requirement: Tunngle is a magic tool that will never let you down (even with the most troublesome games): its LAN emulation features are very powerful and will work with virtually any game that supports IP based LAN gaming.

Tunngle is even more: you can use the Tunngle LAN emulation with virtually any program that has IP based network capabilities. You will never see a complete list of supported programs-games because it would be too long. Everything can work with Tunngle.

Every network comes with a fully functional chat which you can use to communicate with every Tunngler active on that very same network. This chat is a powerful tool to arrange matches or to have some small talk. Bigger networks without LAN capabilities, like the Lobby, can be used for more general chat sessions (for example if you are searching players for a certain game or want to talk about the weather).
Tunngle API is a really powerful tool for all those programs that need to interact with Tunngle itself.
Using this interface, programs and scripts can have Tunngle perform a series of tasks.

For example the API can be used to command Tunngle to jump in and out from networks. The Tunngle API works via a Launcher DLL. In addition, parameters can be passed to the new Tunngle auxiliary process (Launcher EXE).
Each Tunngle Basic client receives a dynamic Tunngle IP upon Login. This IP is refreshed every time one logs in.
*During beta everybody will receive a static IP instead.

Tunngle features a powerful blacklist that will help you keep annoyances at bay. Cheaters, flooders, spammers have no place in the Tunngle Community. Banning is simple and quick. All it takes is a click on the offender nickname. You have the power to decide the duration and scope of the ban.
Tunngle Public Networks are the core of the Tunngle Experience.
One game, one (or more if needed) huge network where all the players from around the world can gather and play online.
It's amazingly simple but yet very innovative. Tunngle Public Networks are a really powerful asset when it comes to have fun and meet new players.
A couple of clicks! That's all it takes to play a game online. Discover the Tunngle Community, be a part of it. In one word: have fun! That's the power of Tunngle Public networks.
As a Tunngle Basic user you can create one Basic Network for up to 32 Tunnglers. You can choose the network name and the password.
Basic Networks aren't shown in the Tunngle Browser and aren't included in the Tunngle Network Search.
A Basic Network will be deleted after three days of inactivity.
It is always possible to recreate the network after it is deleted.
Your Basic private network always comes with one reserved slot just for you.
Private networks are intended to be an integration of our powerful Public Network-Clan Network program. This is the reason why they won't show up in the network browser.

Tunngle uses its own network protocol for all the data transfer. This protocol is extremely fast and secure. Our main focus has been on reliability and performance during all the development stages. We intend to keep it this way.
There are no limits for your creativity. You can use the free Almediadev Skinbuilder to create your own skin in the twinkling of an eye and any audio editor to modify the original sounds.
Personalizing Tunngle for yourself, your friends or your clan couldn't be easier. Just fire up the skin builder and unleash your imagination!
Tunngle uses the internationally approved Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
This encryption algorithm won against its competitors in the year 2000 in a competition of the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST).
We are using the highest possible encryption level that this algorithm provides using a key length of 256 bit.

The keys are exchanged using the secure RSA method with 2048 bit encryption. The abbreviation RSA is composed of the initials of the surnames of the developers Ronald L. Rivest, Adi Shamir und Leonard Adelman. This method was already developed in 1977 and still is the standard for applications that count on secure key exchange because of its mathematical properties.

Tunngle Shares is a cool feature of the Tunngle integrated messenger that allows secure file transfers via an highly encrypted proprietary protocol. Tunngle Shares includes a tight permission control that allows each Tunngler to choose the shared folders and assign the access rights. The embedded download manager supports resuming of aborted/incomplete downloads. Tunngle uses its own protocol and its own rights management system and is designed to be totally independent of Windows file sharing.
Tunngle Shares actively compresses the data that is being transferred. This, where compression is possible, allows faster file transfers and saves your bandwidth for other applications.
Only connections above port 1024 are permitted.
Only use of ICMP, UDP and TCP protocol on IPv4 basis.
This means that there is no access to critical Windows system services.

The C-Class (or B-Class) Emulator, that is active in many Tunngle networks, is indeed a great asset when it comes to gaming. As a matter of fact, a consistent number of games need a special IP range in order to establish a successful Local Area Network connection. This can often be the source of countless headaches during the preparation of the match, because of the bothering Class C/B errors popping all around.

With Tunngle you can forget about these headaches! Tunngle automatically enforces the Class C/B Network type by emulating the required IP range. While you retain your current IP, all the other peers in the network will "receive" a different IP address compatible with yours. This ensures that you can easily create and join LAN games even with the most stubborn games.
